The transit method involves selecting bright stars with high surface brightness and low visual magnitude, as smaller stars block more light from our view. Dips in brightness during transits are detected by monitoring starlight over time using photometric surveys; these dips correspond to a planet's orbital period and shape indicates the planet's size via Kepler's law (dip depth proportional to radius squared). Confirmation often involves multi-exposure data from missions like Kepler or spectroscopy for independent verification.

The radial velocity method observes the Doppler shifts in specific bands of light due to the star's wobble caused by an orbiting planet, leading to periodic motion detected over time with precise photometry. Planets are identified when a measurable radial velocity signal correlates with expected values for planets around stars of known mass (mass proportional to orbital period times planet mass), often confirmed using spectroscopy or Kepler-like data.

\boxed{\begin{array}{l} \textit{Transit method: Select bright stars with high surface brightness and low visual magnitude. Detect dips in brightness during transits by monitoring starlight over time. Confirmation uses Kepler data or spectroscopy to measure planetary mass and radius via Kepler's law (dip depth proportional to planet size squared). } \\ \textit{Radial velocity method: Measure Doppler shifts in specific bands of light due to the star's wobble from a planet, leading to periodic motion detected over time with precise photometry. Planets identified when measurable radial velocity signal correlates with expected values for planets around stars of known mass (mass proportional to orbital period times planet mass), often confirmed using spectroscopy or Kepler-like data. } \end{array}}

